          "body": "Verses 7-8 are the theological center of the chapter and the redemptive hinge of the entire oracle. The same 'in that day' that marked Jacob's stripping now marks a return of sight. The verb *shaah* (to look, to regard, to have regard for) appears in both verses — in v.7 the man looks to his Maker and to the Holy One of Israel; in v.8 he no longer looks to the altars his hands made. The stripping produces the right sight. This is not repentance described sentimentally; it is the logical outcome of having every false confidence removed. When the fortified city disappears (v.3), when the glory fades (v.4), when the harvest yields only gleanings (v.6), there is nothing left to look at except the Holy One. Isaiah's signature divine title appears here: the Holy One of Israel (*qadosh yisrael*) — the transcendently other, morally absolute God who is specifically Israel's covenant God. The title is precisely chosen: the very God Israel had ignored in favor of a Syrian alliance and hand-crafted altars turns out to be the only One remaining when everything else is gone."
